Two days before returning to Beijing from Wuhan, Wang Guangfa ran to fever clinics and temporary isolation wards in several hospitals, not equipped with protective glasses.

Perhaps it was this "fatal" oversight that gave him the virus.

Peking University First Hospital, Director of the Department of respiratory and critical care medicine at the Peking University First Hospital and a member of the COVID-19, traveled to Wuhan with a team of experts from the National Health Commission. After returning to Beijing, he was examined in the hospital on the 21st and was subsequently diagnosed.

Wang Guangfa is currently the only infected health care workers in Beijing. Since the spread of COVID-19,15 medical workers in Wuhan have been confirmed and one suspected case has been reported, according to the city's health commission.

Infection of medical staff is an important sign. Zhong Nanshan, head of the National Health Commission's High Level Expert Group, said it showed that pneumonia was transmitted from person to person.

At a press conference held on January 22 by the state new administration of Health, relevant officials of the National Health Commission said that the occurrence of cases of infection among medical personnel has exposed that there are indeed still some weak links in the prevention and control of hospital infection in medical institutions.

━━━━━

First case of infection among medical staff in Beijing

The outbreak of the new type of coronary pneumonia has entered its 22nd day. On Jan. 22, the Wuhan Union Hospital's fever clinic was filled to capacity, attended by medical staff wearing white protective clothing and attended by doctors who worked for more than 10 hours.

In the small clinic room, the patient who lines up to consult, examine lines up long, almost full of narrow space. Hu Xiang (not his real name) , a health care worker, worries that there is a risk of cross infection and that health care workers can not stay away.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Long queues formed at the Wuhan Union Hospital for consultations and examinations. Xu Wen, Beijing News

A week before COVID-19 became a national concern, hospitals in Beijing had already made a move.

Last week, Zhao Sheng (not his real name) , a respiratory surgeon at a Sanjia hospital in Changping District, was told by the hospital to attend a newly launched training course.

The course, "2020 full training on pneumonia prevention and control knowledge for COVID-19" , is ranked first on the compulsory course platform for continuing medical education in Beijing sponsored by the Beijing Municipal Commission of Health and the Beijing Society of Preventive Medicine. The course consists of four subjects, they are "pneumonia monitoring and management of COVID-19 infection" , "diagnosis and treatment of COVID-19 infection" , "personal protection requirements for Covid-19, laboratory and medical staff" and "interpretation of biosafety guidelines for COVID-19 infection" .

In the course "Covid-19, laboratory and medical personnel personal protection requirements" , the commonly used clinical personal protective equipment, such as eye masks, face masks, face masks and isolation clothing, are introduced in detail, and explained the equipment that should be worn during the diagnosis and treatment, wear the guide, and the corresponding national standards. Course requirements show that you must watch instructional videos and pass an online exam before you can apply for credit.

Zhao Sheng told reporters that all doctors in Beijing receive compulsory training.

In the early hours of January 20, Beijing first reported two cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in Daxing District with a history of travel to Wuhan. In the evening, Beijing Municipal Health Commission reported that the number of confirmed cases in the city increased to 5.

The next day, the reporter saw in many hospitals in Beijing, for the medical staff's protective measures have been upgraded.

"hospitals have stressed the need for protection and doctors have to wear surgical masks and hats when making house calls, " a emergency physician at a Dongcheng District Top-three Hospital told reporters.

The Masks of the emergency medical staff in Peking University Hospital have been upgraded from normal surgical masks to N95 medical protective masks. An expert of the hospital told reporters that after the outbreak, the hospital to emergency, inhalation, pediatric emergency and other high-risk departments focus on the distribution of N95 masks and other materials. Triage desk nurses put on hats, wearing a one-time isolation clothing, hospital corridors, all areas are using clean bacteria tablets for disinfection. At the same time, all patients observed, accompanied by family members are required to wear masks.

"after the outbreak, the level of protection was raised, " the expert said.

The hospital is on alert, not overly cautious. In Wuhan, a city thousands of miles away where the outbreak originated, 15 health care workers have been confirmed infected.

In Beijing, medical workers were also affected. A family member of a staff member at Peking University First Hospital told the Beijing News on Jan. 22 that Wang Guangfa, the head of the respiratory and Critical Care Medicine Department at the hospital, had undergone imaging tests the day before, and that the hospital had issued a confirmation notice.

Reporters from the Hospital of another informed source to verify that Wang Guangfa confirmed infection, and has been designated hospitals under isolation.

On the night of the 22nd, Wang posted on his microblog that he had "finally stopped having a fever today after a day of treatment. ".

"1-story-14" cross-contamination incident

Medical staff were infected, Zhong Nanshan first revealed.

On the afternoon of January 20, in response to the prevention and control of the "COVID-19 pneumonia epidemic" , academician Zhong Nanshan, chairman of the National Health Commission's high-level Expert Group, and other collective answers to reporters' questions, he faced the media for the first time confirmed: There are medical staff infection.

Later came to light the information confirmed that 14 medical staff were infected with the same patient.

In an interview with CCTV on the afternoon of January 21, the Mayor of Wuhan, Zhou Xianwang, gave an account of the "1 story 14" incident.

This cross-infection occurred during Wuhan Union Hospital neurosurgery. Because in neurosurgery, you ignore the fact that a patient has an COVID-19 infection before he's admitted. After the operation, the patient developed a fever, by which time one doctor and 13 nurses had been infected.

Yuen Kwok-yung, professor of microbiology at the University of Hong Kong and a member of the high level expert panel of the National Health Commission, said that infections in such groups were less likely to occur in the medical or infectious diseases departments, because these doctors will be more vigilant.

According to Yuen Kwok-yung, the patient was being treated in brain surgery, but he may have been in close contact with other confirmed patients or had eaten game without a history of contact being presented to the doctor. However, COVID-19 pneumonia may still be latent at the time of admission, with no fever or symptoms of pneumonia, leading to a lack of vigilance on the part of medical staff.

"The lesson is very profound, " Zhou said. "Prevention and control should be thorough and strict in every detail and every link. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medical staff wearing full protective clothing to receive patients. Xu Wen, Beijing News

Looking back 17 years, the history is somewhat similar. On December 22,2002, Zhong Nanshan's Guangzhou Medical University First Affiliated Hospital admitted a pneumonia patient from Heyuan, Guangdong Province. Two days later, all eight paramedics who treated the patient in Heyuan were infected. It was Zhong Nanshan's first SARS patient.

The virus found in this case belongs to the same coronavirus as SARS. According to World Health Organization's website, there are seven known human coronaviruses, four of which are less pathogenic, and two, SARS (Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome) and Mers (Middle East Respiratory Syndrome) , which have caused outbreaks.

Whether in SARS or in this epidemic, infection by medical staff is a very important sign that the pneumonia has passed from person to person.

Dangerous "Aerosol"

Health care workers have always been at high risk of infection.

Statistics from the World Health Organization show that more than 20% of people infected with SARS worldwide are health care workers. At the time of the Mers outbreak, health care workers were also at high risk, with 39 out of 128 cases reported in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, between February 17 and April 26,2014.

Wu Changgui, a former professor at the Fourth Medical University of the People's Liberation Army and a member of the army's Expert Group on smoking, explained that medical personnel can be infected with the pneumonia virus through a variety of channels, including direct contact, such as touching the patient's hands and body, which may bring the virus to the body, into the eyes, conjunctiva, or mouth of a medical professional.

Viruses can also be spread by droplets, which are tiny particles flying around in the atmosphere. The virus attaches itself to droplets several times its size, and the infected person breathes them into the viral droplets and the virus enters the body.

"So we wear masks to filter out the droplets, which acts as a barrier against the virus, " Wu warned. Do not touch the outside of the mask when removing the mask to avoid contact with the virus.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Visiting the new type of pneumonia isolation ward in Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University, the nurse wears isolation clothes to work. Screenshot Video / Beijing News Reporters Ma Jun and Zhao Zhiyuan

Another medium we are not familiar with, may be more dangerous than droplets.

Wu Changgui explained that human beings diffuse the moisture in the air as a gas, and these atomized substances are called "aerosols. ". The particles are much smaller than droplets and can enter the Airways of health care workers, causing transmission of the virus.

Studies by Southeast University and others have shown that, in the last decade or so, there have been multiple outbreaks of respiratory infectious disease, repeatedly indicating that the Bioaerosol emitted by the patient contains large amounts of droplets and droplets containing pathogens, it is an important carrier for transmitting respiratory infectious diseases.

However, Yang Peng, director of the Beijing Center for Disease Control and Prevention's Office of the Beijing Global Health Center, said that whether the virus can be transmitted through Aerosol in this outbreak needs further investigation and study. According to the characteristics of previous coronavirus, droplet transmission and contact transmission are the main forms of transmission.

Regardless of the route of transmission, it is recognized that front-line medical staff is a high-risk group, tracheal intubation, tracheotomy and other clinical treatment means, are high-risk operations. Wang Linghang, director of Infectious Diseases Emergency Department at Temple of Earth Hospital in Beijing, said that the resistance of medical staff is no different from that of ordinary people, and that in winter and spring, in addition to new types of pneumonia, there is also an influenza epidemic, which means greater pressure for prevention and control.

Wu Changgui believes that for infectious pneumonia, the risk of infection of medical staff is significantly higher than the general population. "The average person is exposed to an environment that can be infected with the pneumonia virus, and the risk of infection is higher for health workers who deal directly with patients with pneumonia, whether they are exposed to suspected or confirmed patients. "

"there is a weak link. "

"We are also saddened to see cases of infection among medical staff. Medical staff is indeed a high-risk occupation, " said Jiao Yahui, head of the Medical Administration and Hospital Authority of the National Health Commission.

Wang Guangfa was also curious about when he was infected with the virus. While working in Wuhan, Mingming had been wearing N95 masks and even a splash screen throughout the hospital, almost "fully armed. ".

He recalls going to the fever clinic and the temporary isolation ward two days before returning to Beijing without goggles. That could be when the virus entered his conjunctiva.

At a press conference held on January 22, Jiao Yahui said there had been cases of infection among medical staff, providing evidence of human-to-human transmission. On the other hand, also exposed the medical institutions in the hospital infection prevention and control, there are indeed some weak links.

Jiao Yahui explained that this and the harm and spread of the virus, initially did not reach such a high level related. "We have come to understand the progression of the disease, " he said. "The disease has a process of development and change, with different characteristics in the early stages and now, so protection and hospital infection control measures need to be adjusted accordingly. "

This process also happened during the SARS period.

A study conducted by the Guangdong Pharmaceutical University, the Public Health and the Guangzhou Eighth People's Hospital showed that, the risk of SARS infection was significantly higher among workers who did not use protective clothing, masks, eye masks and gloves when they first came into contact with SARS patients.

During the epidemic of that year, there was a distinct curve of infection among medical staff ————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————. This is because, after the outbreak, medical staff to strengthen personal protection, government departments have also put forward comprehensive prevention and control measures.

"personal awareness-building and the availability of protective measures are an important aspect of reducing infection, " the study noted.

More stringent control measures

CCTV reporters recently visited the intensive care isolation ward of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital and found that medical staff should wear isolation clothing, shoe covers, gloves and masks, and N95 masks when entering the ward. Before entering the intensive care unit, medical staff have to pass through the air shower channel, ultraviolet disinfection area disinfection.

"In general, fever clinics should carry out standard prevention and wear surgical masks for medical care. Once a suspected case is diagnosed, medical institutions should upgrade the protection level, including wearing N95 masks, protective clothing and face screens, " Yang said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Surgical mask can prevent the spread of droplets, N95 mask more airtight, can prevent the spread of aerosols.

Jiao Yahui, the current National Health Commission has taken a series of measures. On the one hand, revised and improved standards and norms of personal protection for medical personnel; on the other hand, more stringent measures for the prevention and control of hospital infection were proposed. The completion of these technical programmes will be followed by training of medical personnel throughout the country.

Wu Changgui believes that from 2003 to the present, 17 years have passed since the prevention and treatment of SARS, the protective measures for medical personnel have been relatively complete. "In practice, protection does not have to be complex, but even a good level of protection can not completely isolate the health care worker from the patient and reduce the risk of infection to zero. "

Wuhan NEW PNEUMONIA ISOLATION WARD: Nurses wearing protective clothing for 12 hours, not a sip of water. Beijing News Video Production (ID: Wevideo)

"The emergence of the infection in the medical staff also reminds us that we should be highly alert to the prevention and control of hospital infection and the early detection of patients, not only in departments related to patient infection, but also in other departments related to non-infection, " Jiao Yahui said. The National Health Commission will further take more stringent prevention and control measures to ensure the treatment of patients, as well as to protect the personal protection and safety of medical staff.

However, in the face of the face mask on the market by the emergency period, the hospital also faced difficulties. A doctor told the Beijing News reporter, N95 mask material tension, and can not cover the entire staff, at present only supply emergency department, Smoking Department and other major departments.

When the reporter visited the Peking Union Medical College Hospital, he also found that the hospital's emergency department, Fever Clinic staff wearing N95 masks, in the lobby of the clinic, there are many medical staff wearing general surgical masks walking.

"It's not just the emergency department, the fever clinic, and the smoking department that has access to patients, " the doctor said, noting that patients who have chest x-rays or CT scans may also be at risk of infection.

Hubei's mask stock has also been "urgent. ". January 22 afternoon news, as the province can only produce 8 million medical masks, 2 million sets of protective clothing, infrared thermometer 1200 sets, can not meet the province's epidemic prevention needs. Hubei Province plans to request urgent support from the state, allocating 40 million medical masks, 5 million protective clothing, and 5,000 infrared thermometers.

Wuhan has opened a 24-hour hotline to receive donations from the public, and there is a shortage of medical supplies such as goggles and protective clothing. Beijing News Our video production (ID: Wevideo)

On January 23, the Ministry of Industry and Information Technology officially announced that, according to the requirements of the joint prevention and control mechanism of the epidemic situation, in the early hours of January 23, the Ministry of Industry and Information Technology of the People's Republic of China has arranged an emergency transfer of 10,000 protective suits and 50,000 gloves from the Central Medical Reserve to Wuhan.
